Developer Reading Guide
For a developer who can build websites but is new to this document set
1. Purpose of This Guide
This guide explains what documents to read, in what order to read them, and what you are expected to learn from each one.

You are not being asked to read everything at once and hold it all in your head. You are reading in a sequence so you can answer these questions in the right order:

1.	What kind of system is this?
2.	What is this specific website supposed to do?
3.	What exact settings and values must I use?
4.	How is the solution organized?
5.	How are pages and modules supposed to be built?
6.	How is the chosen technology stack supposed to implement all of that?

The documents are separated on purpose. Each one answers a different kind of question. The goal is to understand the role of each document so you know where to look when you need something.

2. Reading Sequence
Read the documents in this order:

7.	Document 1 — Website Solution System Framework
8.	Document 10 — Developer Handoff Brief
9.	Document 2 — Website Specification
10.	Document 4 — Site Configuration Record
11.	Document 3 — Site Configuration Standard
12.	Document 5 — Website Solution Architecture Standard
13.	Document 6 — Website Realization and Page Composition Standard
14.	Document 7 — Developer Handbook
15.	Document 9 — Technical Build Profile, only when it is fully filled in and approved

This sequence starts with the overall map, then moves to the project itself, then to the requirements and actual values, then to structure and page-building rules, and finally to the technical implementation layer.

3. What to Read and What You Should Learn
Document 1 — Website Solution System Framework
Read this first, once.

Read it to understand the map of the whole system.

This document explains:
•	why there are multiple documents
•	what each document is for
•	what belongs in each document
•	how the documents relate to each other
•	why local invention is not allowed when something is already governed elsewhere

What you should learn
–	The Website Specification tells you what must be built
–	The Site Configuration Record gives you the current approved settings and values for this site
–	The Site Configuration Standard explains how those settings and values are structured
–	The Architecture Standard explains how the solution is organized
–	The Realization Standard explains how pages, modules, and components are built
–	The Technical Build Profile explains how the chosen stack implements the governed system

What you should know after reading it
You should be able to tell which document to check when you have:
•	a requirements question
•	a settings or values question
•	a configuration-structure question
•	a structure question
•	a page-building question
•	a stack-specific technical question

Important note:  This is an overview document. It is not your day-to-day build document.

Document 10 — Developer Handoff Brief
Read this second.

Read it to understand this specific website project.

This document explains:
•	what the site is
•	what sections it includes
•	what the build priorities are
•	what should be built first
•	which documents matter most during implementation

What you should learn
–	what the project is trying to deliver
–	what counts as P1, P2, and P3
–	what the first implementation priorities are
–	how to enter the project without trying to use every document all at once

What you should know after reading it
•	what this site is
•	what matters most in the current phase
•	what should be built first
•	which documents you will use most often during implementation

Important note:  This is your entry document for the project.

Document 2 — Website Specification
Read this third.

Read it to understand what must be built.

This document explains:
•	site goals and priorities
•	users and needs
•	navigation and information architecture
•	content model and content types
•	page and view requirements
•	inquiry and lead-capture behavior
•	CMS requirements
•	accessibility, search, URL, and responsive requirements
•	acceptance criteria

What you should learn
–	what pages are required
–	what flows are required
–	what content types the CMS must support
–	what the site must do
–	what the CMS must do
–	what the build must satisfy before it can be accepted

What you should know after reading it
You should be able to answer:
•	what pages and flows are mandatory
•	what the CMS must support
•	what behavior is required versus preferred
•	what conditions must be met for the build to be accepted

Important note:  This is the main requirements document.

Document 4 — Site Configuration Record
Read this fourth.

Read it to understand the current approved settings and values for this site.

This document contains:
•	the active design selection
•	the current scheme
•	typography values
•	spacing values
•	radius values
•	navigation labels and order
•	operational text and messages
•	status labels
•	SEO and metadata values where applicable

What you should learn
–	which theme is active
–	which typography, spacing, and radius settings are active
–	which labels, messages, and statuses are already defined
–	which navigation values are approved
–	which values the implementation must consume directly

What you should know after reading it
You should be able to answer:
•	what exact visual values to use
•	what exact labels and messages to use
•	what exact status values to use
•	what exact navigation labels and order to use
•	what you must not invent on your own because it is already defined here

Important note:  This document contains the current approved settings and values for the site. It must follow the structure and rules defined in the Site Configuration Standard.

Document 3 — Site Configuration Standard
Read this after Document 4.

Read it to understand how the settings in Document 4 are organized.

This document explains:
•	the configuration model
•	what a family is
•	what a scheme is
•	what a preset is
•	what current selection means
•	how configuration is structured
•	how configuration is validated
•	what the record is allowed to contain

What you should learn
–	why the values in Document 4 are structured the way they are
–	how the configuration model works
–	how different configuration objects relate to each other
–	what the implementation must respect when reading or exposing settings

What you should know after reading it
You should be able to answer:
•	what kinds of settings are allowed
•	how those settings are grouped and validated
•	why the implementation must follow a defined configuration path instead of inventing local settings or shortcuts

Important note:  Document 4 tells you the current approved values. Document 3 tells you the structure and rules behind those values.

Document 5 — Website Solution Architecture Standard
Read this after Documents 2 and 4.

Read it to understand how the solution is organized at a structural level.

This document explains structural responsibilities such as:
•	content access
•	content normalization
•	configuration resolution
•	navigation and route structure
•	experience assembly
•	shared presentation
•	section-specific presentation
•	interaction handling
•	metadata and discoverability

What you should learn
–	how different responsibilities are separated
–	what kind of concern belongs in which structural area
–	why structure is different from UI components and page content
–	why some concerns must stay separate instead of being mixed together

What you should know after reading it
You should be able to answer:
•	where a concern belongs structurally
•	what should remain separate
•	why content access, configuration resolution, rendering, page assembly, and interaction handling are not the same thing

Important note:  This is the structure document. It is about how the solution is organized, not about page-level UI pieces.

Document 6 — Website Realization and Page Composition Standard
Read this after Document 5.

Read it to understand how the structural model turns into actual build work.

This document explains:
•	what a buildable module is
•	what a reusable component is
•	what a page type is
•	what a page instance is
•	how page composition works
•	what the CMS may and may not vary
•	what kinds of modules and components are allowed

What you should learn
–	how pages are assembled
–	what counts as a module
–	what counts as a smaller reusable component
–	where page rules live
–	where module rules live
–	where CMS control starts and stops

What you should know after reading it
You should be able to answer:
•	what parts of the site are modules
•	what parts are reusable components
•	what kind of page types exist
•	how a page is put together
•	what editors are allowed to vary and what they are not allowed to vary

Important note:  Document 5 explains structure. Document 6 explains how that structure is realized as pages, modules, components, and composition rules.

Document 7 — Developer Handbook
Read this after Documents 5 and 6.

Read it to understand how the system works in practice.

This document gives:
•	practical distinctions
•	examples
•	operational explanations
•	simple ways to think about pages, modules, components, and page instances

What you should learn
–	how the ideas in Documents 5 and 6 look in real work
–	how to interpret the model while building
–	how to decide where something belongs when you are unsure

What you should know after reading it
You should be able to answer:
•	how to apply the document system while building a page
•	how to think through common cases in a practical way
•	how to avoid confusing modules, components, and page rules during implementation

Important note:  This is a guidance document. It helps you use the system, but it is not the main authority for requirements or values.

Document 9 — Technical Build Profile
Read this last, and only when it is fully filled in and approved.

Read it to understand the selected stack and the technical implementation rules.

This document explains:
•	which technologies are selected
•	why they were selected
•	where responsibilities live in the code
•	how configuration is resolved at runtime
•	what technical contracts and boundaries must be preserved
•	what technical rules the implementation must follow

What you should learn
–	how the governed system is implemented in the chosen stack
–	how runtime configuration flows
–	what the technical boundaries are
–	what contracts and mappings the implementation must preserve

What you should know after reading it
You should be able to answer:
•	which stack is in use
•	where major responsibilities live technically
•	how the configuration reaches the runtime
•	what technical boundaries and rules you must not break

Important note:  Do not treat this as active technical authority until it is fully filled in and approved.

