6. What Your Main Working Documents Will Be After Onboarding
After this first full reading pass, the documents you will use most often during normal implementation will usually be:

•	Document 10 for task orientation
•	Document 2 for requirements
•	Document 4 for approved settings and values
•	Document 6 for module and page-building questions

You should still understand Documents 3, 5, 7, and 9, but you will usually open them when a specific question requires them.

7. When Something Is Unclear
Do not invent missing settings, missing structure, or missing rules on your own.

Use this path:

•	requirement question → Document 2
•	approved settings and values question → Document 4
•	configuration structure question → Document 3
•	structure question → Document 5
•	module or page-building question → Document 6
•	practical interpretation question → Document 7
•	stack-specific technical question → Document 9, only when active

If the answer is still not clear after checking the right document, stop and escalate instead of guessing.

Use this message:

“I am building ____. I checked Document __, Section __. I still cannot determine ____.  ”

That is the correct behavior. Do not fill the gap by guessing.

8. Final Working Rule
Use the full sequence once to understand the system.

After that:

•	use Document 10 to stay oriented
•	use Document 2 to know what must be built
•	use Document 4 to know what exact values to use
•	use Document 6 when the question is about modules, pages, or composition
•	use Documents 3, 5, 7, and 9 when the question specifically calls for them

That is the intended way to work with this document set.
